VERSION: 1.4.0

Overview
========
ambed is a multi-mode digital voice transcoder daemon that bridges between
different amateur radio digital voice protocols. It uses DVSI hardware
vocoders for AMBE+/AMBE2+ and software vocoders for Codec2 (M17) and
IMBE (P25).


Supported Codecs
================
- AMBE+     (D-Star) - hardware DVSI vocoder
- AMBE2+    (DMR/YSF/NXDN) - hardware DVSI vocoder
- Codec2    (M17) - software vocoder (3200bps mode)
- IMBE      (P25) - software vocoder


Hardware Compatibility
======================
This version of ambed is compatible with:
- DF2ET's AMBE3003USB opensource device (https://github.com/phl0/AMBE3003USB)
- LX3JL's USB-3006 opensource device (https://github.com/lx3jl/usb-3006)
- DVSI's USB-3000 device
- DVSI's USB-3003 device
- DVSI's USB-3012 device
- NWDR's ThumbDV device
- NWDR's ThumbDV-3 device
- DVMEGA AMBE3000 device
- DVMEGA AMBE3003 device

Available transcoding channels per device:

Device              Hardware    Transcoding     Software Vocoders
                    Channels    Channels        (IMBE/Codec2)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
3000 (pair)         2           2               1 each
3003 (single)       3           2               1 each
3003 (pair)         6           6               3 each
3003+3000 (pair)    4           4               2 each
3006                6           6               3 each
3012                12          12              6 each

Notes:
- USB-3000 devices must be used in pairs or paired with a USB-3003
- Multiple devices can be used simultaneously
- Avoid USB hubs as they may cause unreliable behaviour
- Max concurrent streams is calculated automatically from hardware
- Software vocoders (Codec2/IMBE) use 2 hardware channels per stream


Configuration Options (main.h)
==============================

QoS/DSCP Marking:
    DSCP_MARKING_ENABLE     1 = enable, 0 = disable
    DSCP_VALUE              DSCP value 0-63 (default: 46/EF for voice)

Audio Processing:
    USE_AGC                 1 = AGC enabled, 0 = fixed gain
    AGC_CLAMPING            AGC gain limit in dB (default: 3)
    USE_BANDPASSFILTER      1 = 300-3400Hz bandpass filter enabled

Transcoding Gains (hardware AMBE<->AMBE):
    CODECGAIN_AMBEPLUS      D-Star decode/encode gain (default: -10dB)
    CODECGAIN_AMBE2PLUS     DMR decode/encode gain (default: +10dB)

IMBE Transcoding Gains (P25 input):
    IMBE_DECODE_GAIN        IMBE decoder output gain (default: +18dB)
    IMBE_TO_AMBEPLUS_GAIN   Additional gain for D-Star output (default: 0dB)
    IMBE_TO_AMBE2PLUS_GAIN  Additional gain for DMR output (default: -13dB)
    IMBE_TO_CODEC2_GAIN     Gain for M17 output (default: -7dB)

Codec2 Transcoding Gains (M17 input):
    CODEC2_DECODE_GAIN      Codec2 decoder output gain (default: +6dB)
    CODEC2_TO_AMBEPLUS_GAIN Gain for D-Star output (default: 0dB)
    CODEC2_TO_AMBE2PLUS_GAIN Gain for DMR output (default: -16dB)
    CODEC2_TO_IMBE_GAIN     Gain for P25 output (default: -8dB)

Timeouts:
    STREAM_ACTIVITY_TIMEOUT Stream inactivity timeout in seconds (default: 3)


Installation
============

1) Install FTDI drivers

Download from FTDI web site the latest D2XX driver package (tested on 1.4.6).
Follow FTDI provided documentation for installation and testing of the drivers.


2) Install build tools

# apt-get install build-essential
# apt-get install g++


3) Download and compile ambed

# git clone https://github.com/LX3JL/xlxd.git
# cd xlxd/ambed/
# make clean
# make
# make install


4) Configure ambed startup script

# nano /ambed/run

Edit the following line to match your IP:

sudo /ambed/ambed 127.0.0.1 &

If ambed is running on the same machine as xlxd, use 127.0.0.1
Otherwise use the machine's own IP address.


5) Running ambed

Note:
Due to specific FTDI driver implementation, ambed must run with root
privileges and cannot be run as a daemon. ambed will display information
and error messages in the terminal from which it was started.

Plug in at least one USB-3xxx device, then:

# cd /ambed
# ./run

During initialisation, ambed will scan all USB ports to discover,
configure and report the status of all available USB-3xxx devices.

Example startup output:
    Starting AMBEd 1.4.0
    Codec interfaces initialized successfully : 6 channels available
    Software vocoders : 3 IMBE (P25), 3 Codec2 (M17)
    Max concurrent streams: 3 (from 6 vocoder channels)
    Voice packets marked as DSCP 46
    AMBEd started and listening on 127.0.0.1


6) Stopping ambed

Find the PID of ambed process:

# ps ax | grep ambed

And kill the process:

# kill xxxx

Where xxxx is the PID found previously.


Transcoding Paths
=================

Hardware (DVSI) paths:
    D-Star (AMBE+) <-> DMR/YSF/NXDN (AMBE2+)

Software codec paths:
    M17 (Codec2) -> D-Star (AMBE+)
    M17 (Codec2) -> DMR/YSF/NXDN (AMBE2+)
    M17 (Codec2) -> P25 (IMBE)
    P25 (IMBE) -> D-Star (AMBE+)
    P25 (IMBE) -> DMR/YSF/NXDN (AMBE2+)
    P25 (IMBE) -> M17 (Codec2)

Note: M17 and P25 input modes use software decoders paired with
hardware encoders. Each stream uses 2 hardware channels.

